 :tx/rationale "Create task: CCE-PROMPT: Concept-aware DOGFOOD agent prompts — teach braid-native methodology. CONTEXT: DOGFOOD-2 Sessions 1 and 2 used prompts that said 'use braid observe to record findings.' These prompts treated braid as a WRITE-ONLY JOURNAL. The agents never checked connections, never followed steering questions, never used concept vocabulary. The prompt IS part of the system (ADR-FOUNDATION-016: seeds/prompts are projections from the store). Testing CCE with old prompts would test nothing — the new architecture needs prompts that teach agents to USE the concept-aware responses. THE INSIGHT: When the agent observes something, braid responds with concept membership, structural gaps, and a steering question. The prompt must teach the agent to READ and FOLLOW these responses. This is the bidirectional Markov blanket: agent shapes braid's knowledge, braid shapes the agent's attention. Without prompt changes, the blanket is unidirectional (agent → braid only). APPROACH: Revise the 3 DOGFOOD agent prompts (Architecture, Code Review, Spec Audit) to include: (1) After every braid observe, READ the response. If braid names a concept, USE that concept name in future observations. If braid identifies a structural gap, INVESTIGATE that gap next. If braid asks a steering question, ATTEMPT TO ANSWER IT before moving on. (2) After every braid status, READ the concept inventory and coverage map. Use the FRONTIER list to choose the next investigation area. (3) Use --tag with concept names that braid has surfaced (not invented tags — use braid's vocabulary). (4) If braid assigns an observation to the wrong concept, observe a correction: 'this observation is about X, not Y' — this teaches braid to refine concept boundaries. (5) Check braid status every 3-4 observations to monitor concept formation and coverage progress. The prompts should NOT instruct agents on braid internals. They should model a NATURAL WORKFLOW: observe, read response, follow leads, check progress. The concept vocabulary emerges from the interaction, not from instructions. ACCEPTANCE: (A) Three revised prompts (Architecture, Code Review, Spec Audit) in scripts/ or docs/. (B) Each prompt includes the 5 behavioral instructions above. (C) Prompts do NOT explain braid internals (embeddings, centroids, etc.) — only observable behavior. (D) Prompts are tested on a dry-run: one human read-through verifying the instructions are clear and natural. FILE: scripts/dogfood_agent_a_prompt.md, scripts/dogfood_agent_b_prompt.md, scripts/dogfood_agent_c_prompt.md. DEPENDS-ON: CCE-5 (steering responses must exist before prompts can reference them). BLOCKS: CCE-GATE (DOGFOOD-3 must use concept-aware prompts). TRACES-TO: ADR-FOUNDATION-016 (Observation-Projection Duality — prompts are projections of methodology)."
